Heil wants to check other industries after meat industry
The corona crisis brought the conditions in parts of the meat industry to light again.
Legislation is about to be tightened.
But are they right - and will they remain so?
Federal Labor Minister Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to check other industries after the now planned strict regulations against maladministration in the meat industry.
"We will look at industry by industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if necessary," Heil told the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
After the mass corona outbreak at the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet wants to pass a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to use external personnel for slaughter, cutting and meat processing.
For this purpose, the use of contract and temporary workers should be prohibited there.
Employer President Ingo Kramer told the dpa:"Stay away from a general restriction of work contracts and temporary employment, if you do not want to completely choke off the economy".
Contracts for work and services are, for example, for wide areas of the craft, construction industry and plant construction necessarily the basis for their value creation at the customer.
"The misdeeds of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument".
Heil assured:"My goal is not to ban work contracts everywhere in the German economy".
Work contracts make sense.
"When an industrial company commissions a craftsman to install a safety system, this is a normal contract for work."
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary work in its industry alone to be unconstitutional.
It is not explainable, why in the portioning and packaging of cheese should apply in the future different labor law than sausage, it says in a statement on the proposed law, as the" Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung " (Saturday) reports.
A ban would therefore increase the consumer price by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
According to the results of an audit by the NRW Occupational Safety and Health Administration, Eastern European employees from work contract companies often worked in the industry, sometimes 16 hours a day.
Often they did not have a break.
Wages were withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also noted that the situation with the accommodation of employees was often miserable.
Heil said a relatively sharp law had already come into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, these were circumvented by" tricky constructions".
"Now we have to clean up fundamentally".
The politician announced:"In the Occupational Health and Safety Act, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, are also measures that affect not only the meat industry - for example, higher inspection rates for occupational health and safety or clear criteria for shared accommodation".
The draft of the dpa includes amendments to the Law on the Protection of Workers ' Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Consumer Protection Minister Ursula Nonnemacher (Greens) considers more intensive controls necessary.
"I would like us to be able to carry out even more inspections in many supervisory areas: food inspections, animal welfare, everything possible, including animal transport, "said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB broadcast"Brandenburg aktuell".
But more controls would also require more staff positions.
