Baden-Württemberg: More than 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart-Despite all the threatened penalties and court rulings, motorists continue to accelerate in countless illegal races on the streets of Baden-Württemberg: Last year and the first four months of this year, the police in the southwest have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
There are no comparable figures for the years before, but the speedsters are increasingly making work for the judicial authorities: In 2018, a total of 155 investigations for illegal races were conducted at the public prosecutor's offices between Konstanz and Mannheim, a year later there were already 252 and in the current year until the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the response of the Ministry of the Interior to a request from the Landtag SPD.
In most cases, the drivers spontaneously competed against each other or they fled the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
At the wheel were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 Fines-15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the speeding drivers caught and also asked to pay: According to the Interior Ministry, a total of 113 fines have been imposed since 2018 and 15 prison sentences have been pronounced.
However, there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, other motorists reacted more sensitively than before because of the several tragic accidents and processes of past years and indicated more often, said a ministry spokesman.
The Autobahn 8 is particularly popular with racers. Drivers repeatedly slow down the traffic there in order to gain space and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
A81 is most popular "racetrack"
On the A81, the police register even more races than on any other federal highway.
A speed limit is used there to try to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The usually high-priced and revamped sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers dodge to Germany because of the high penalties for driving too fast and car races in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few routes: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on highways," says Martin Rivoir, the transport expert of the SPD parliamentary group.
"The inhibition threshold for speeders would be significantly higher if you were not allowed to travel legally here and there with 200 kilometers per hour and more".
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: "Anyone who disregards all the rules in such a way and puts not only their own life but also the lives of other road users at risk is hardly achievable with reason".
ADAC calls for stronger police crackdown
However, this is not enough for ADAC: "We assume that speeding drivers will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, Head of the Transport and Environment department at ADAC Württemberg.
It calls for additional and also tougher controls on the affected routes.
Not infrequently, the high-speed showdown becomes more painful and serious: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people died in the races nationwide, two of them uninvolved in a night crash in Stuttgart's city center and one in Gerlingen.
Two young men are said to have run a car race there in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, hit a garden wall and remained on its side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
21 other people were injured in the races of the past two years.
However, in the opinion of Interior Minister Thomas Strobl, tougher penalties are not necessary:" Legislative action to sanction illegal motor vehicle races harder is not seen, " says the Interior Ministry paper.
